self.__next_f.push([1,"Animate a 3D element between layout positions on scroll We get asked how to animate a 3D object between waypoints in a page a lot in the GSAP forums. It is especially popular with 3D product models like soda cans. Here's a demo that simplifies down the approach.  We will be using ScrollTrigger and the FLIP plugin. Treat your 3D canvas like a card you can move In this example we're creating a small Three.js scene and rendering it into a \u003ccanvas/\u003e element. Inside this canvas is a cube, but you could swap in any 3D content. The important part is that the canvas element is the thing we're going to tell Flip plugin to move.  We added a few marker elements in the layout. These markers are just empty targets that represent the positions you want to move to. Make sure they exist in the normal flow and have measurable size. \u003cdiv class=\"main\"\u003e  \u003cdiv class=\"container initial\"\u003e    \u003ccanvas/\u003e   \u003c/div\u003e  \u003cdiv class=\"container second\"\u003e    \u003cdiv class=\"marker\"\u003e\u003c/div\u003e  \u003c/div\u003e  \u003cdiv class=\"container third\"\u003e    \u003cdiv class=\"marker\"\u003e\u003c/div\u003e  \u003c/div\u003e\u003c/div\u003e   Flip between markers using Flip.getState() + Flip.fit() Capture the states of your marker targets, then let Flip.fit() animate the canvas between them. Flip will measure each the marker elements and then fit the canvas to each marker’s state.  We're also adding some extra animations to the timeline to affect the rotation of the cube. const s2 = Flip.getState(\".second .marker\");const s3 = Flip.getState(\".third .marker\");const tl = gsap.timeline({...});// Hop to second marker and rotate the cubetl.add(Flip.fit(canvasEl, s2, { duration: 1, ease: \"none\" })).to(mesh.rotation, {   x: `+=${Math.PI}`,   y: `+=${Math.PI}`,   duration: 1,   ease: \"none\" },\"\u003c\")// A little breathing room between hops.addLabel(\"mid\", \"+=0.5\")// Hop to third marker and rotate again.add(Flip.fit(canvasEl, s3, { duration: 1, ease: \"none\" }), \"mid\").to(mesh.rotation,{   x: `+=${Math.PI}`,   y: `+=${Math.PI}`,   duration: 1,   ease: \"none\" },\"\u003c\");   Clean resizing with gsap.context() This bit is very important. ScrollTrigger pre-calculates and caches values for performance, whereas Flip is dynamic and needs to measure the current layout at the time the animation fires. If the page resizes and you do not rebuild the timeline, Flip will be using stale measurements and your animations will look broken.  To make this nice and easy we wrap our animations in a gsap.context(). On resize, we call ctx.revert() to clean up any timelines and ScrollTriggers created inside, then rebuild so Flip can re-measure. function buildTimeline() {  ctx \u0026\u0026 ctx.revert(); // If the context exists, revert it and rebuild so the FLIP animations are recalculated on resize and reflect the new layout    // collect all of our animations in a GSAP context  ctx = gsap.context(() =\u003e {    const tl = gsap.timeline({      scrollTrigger: {        start: 0,        end: \"max\",        scrub: 2      }    });    ...  });}addEventListener(\"resize\", () =\u003e {  buildTimeline();});  "])

